#Approach:

Approach:
Ye code har element ka contribution nikalta hai as minimum of subarrays.

1. Har arr[i] ke liye do cheeze nikaali gayi hain:
   - PSE = Previous Smaller Element ka index
   - NSE = Next Smaller Element ka index
2. In dono se pata chalta hai ki arr[i] kitne subarrays me minimum ban sakta hai.
3. Left choices = i - pse[i]
   Right choices = nse[i] - i
4. Total subarrays jisme arr[i] minimum hoga:
   left * right
5. To arr[i] ka contribution:
   arr[i] * left * right
6. Sab elements ka contribution add karke final answer milta hai.

Main idea:
Har subarray alag se generate nahi kar rahe.
Bas ye count kar rahe hain ki koi element minimum kitni baar ban raha hai.

Important edge point:
- PSE me '>' use kiya hai
- NSE me '>=' use kiya hai
Ye duplicate elements ke case me double counting avoid karne ke liye kiya gaya hai.

Time Complexity: O(n)
Space Complexity: O(n)

#Code:

class Solution {
    public int sumSubarrayMins(int[] arr) {

        int[] pse = findPse(arr);
        int[] nse = findNse(arr);
        long total = 0;
        int mod = (int)(1e9 + 7);

        for(int i=0; i<arr.length; i++){
            int left = i - pse[i];
            int right = nse[i] - i;
            long contri = (right * left) % mod;
            contri = (contri * arr[i]) % mod;

            total = (total + contri) % mod;
        }

        return (int)total;
    }

    private int[] findNse(int[] arr){
        Deque<Integer> stack = new ArrayDeque<>();
        int n = arr.length;
        int[] nse = new int[n];

        for(int i=n-1; i>=0; i--){
            while(!stack.isEmpty() && arr[stack.peek()] >= arr[i]){
                stack.pop();
            }

            nse[i] = stack.isEmpty() ? n : stack.peek();
            stack.push(i);
        }
        return nse;
    }

    private int[] findPse(int[] arr){
        Deque<Integer> stack = new ArrayDeque<>();
        int n = arr.length;
        int[] pse = new int[n];

        for(int i=0; i<n; i++){
            //Why there is no = sign in while condition ?
            // Because of an edge case where elements are same say 1,1. In this case
            // the 1st index element 1 will duplicate a subarray that has already been calculated as a result 
            // to eliminate this edge case, we didn't use = sign
            while(!stack.isEmpty() && arr[stack.peek()] > arr[i]){
                stack.pop();
            }

            pse[i] = stack.isEmpty() ? -1 : stack.peek();
            stack.push(i);
        }
        return pse;
    }
}
